    "trap": "After reaching the conjugate $\\dfrac{y^2}{12}-\\dfrac{x^2}{3}=1$, reading off $a^2,b^2$ from habit as if $x^2$ still carried the transverse axis. For a hyperbola the transverse semi-axis squared sits under the POSITIVE term, here $y^2$, so $a^2=12,\\ b^2=3$ and $e'^2=1+\\tfrac{b^2}{a^2}=\\tfrac54$. Swapping them ($a^2=3,b^2=12$) gives $e'^2=1+\\tfrac{12}{3}=5$, i.e. $e'=\\sqrt5$ — which is in fact the eccentricity of the ORIGINAL hyperbola, not its conjugate. The tell-tale check $\\tfrac1{e^2}+\\tfrac1{e'^2}=1$ then fails, since $\\tfrac15+\\tfrac15\\neq1$.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Constant-difference family",
        "steps": [
          "The asymptote pair is $(2x-y)(2x+y)=4x^2-y^2=0$. A hyperbola with these asymptotes differs from the pair only by a constant: $4x^2-y^2=k$. Through $(2,2)$: $16-4=12$, so $S:\\,4x^2-y^2-12=0$.",
          "Choose $\\lambda$ so that $S+\\lambda=0$ is the asymptote pair: $4x^2-y^2-12+\\lambda=0$ must equal $4x^2-y^2=0$, giving $\\lambda=12$. Thus the pair is the arithmetic mean $S+\\lambda$ of the family.",
          "The conjugate is the next member, $S+2\\lambda$: $4x^2-y^2-12+24=0\\Rightarrow 4x^2-y^2=-12$, i.e. $\\dfrac{y^2}{12}-\\dfrac{x^2}{3}=1$.",
          "For this conjugate the positive term is $y^2$, so $a^2=12,\\ b^2=3$, giving $e'^2=1+\\tfrac{3}{12}=\\tfrac54\\Rightarrow e'=\\tfrac{\\sqrt5}{2}$. $\\boxed{\\tfrac{y^2}{12}-\\tfrac{x^2}{3}=1,\\ e'=\\tfrac{\\sqrt5}{2}}$"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Direct conjugate flip",
        "steps": [
          "Write the hyperbola in standard form: dividing $4x^2-y^2=12$ by $12$ gives $\\tfrac{x^2}{3}-\\tfrac{y^2}{12}=1$. Its conjugate is obtained by replacing $+1$ with $-1$: $\\tfrac{x^2}{3}-\\tfrac{y^2}{12}=-1\\Rightarrow\\tfrac{y^2}{12}-\\tfrac{x^2}{3}=1$, sharing the same asymptotes $4x^2-y^2=0$.",
          "Eccentricity of the conjugate (transverse axis along $y$, $a^2=12,b^2=3$): $e'^2=1+\\tfrac{3}{12}=\\tfrac54$, so $e'=\\tfrac{\\sqrt5}{2}$.",
          "Consistency: the original has $e^2=1+\\tfrac{12}{3}=5$, and a hyperbola–conjugate pair must satisfy $\\tfrac1{e^2}+\\tfrac1{e'^2}=1$. Indeed $\\tfrac15+\\tfrac{4}{5}=1$. $\\boxed{e'=\\tfrac{\\sqrt5}{2}}$"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "Insight: the asymptote pair sits exactly halfway between a hyperbola and its conjugate as a one-parameter family $S+t$ — recognising the asymptotes as the degenerate mean ($S+\\lambda$) reconstructs the whole family from a single point. The relation $\\tfrac1{e^2}+\\tfrac1{e'^2}=1$ is the perfect self-check: any axis-swap slip breaks it instantly."
